T1  - A Quantity-Driven Theory of Term Premia and Exchange Rates*
PY  - 2023
Y1  - 2023/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjad024
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 138
IS  - 4
SP  - 2327
EP  - 2389
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We develop a model in which specialized bond investors must absorb shocks to the supply and demand for long-term bonds in two currencies. Since long-term bonds and foreign exchange are both exposed to unexpected movements in short-term interest rates, a shift in the supply of long-term bonds in one currency influences the foreign exchange rate between the two currencies, as well as bond term premia in both currencies. Our model matches several important empirical patterns, including the comovement between exchange rates and term premia, and the finding that central banks’ quantitative easing policies affect exchange rates. An extension of our model links spot exchange rates to the persistent deviations from covered interest rate parity that have emerged since 2008.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjad024
ER  - 



